{
  "text": "It has been shown that the C-terminal domain of the β-subunit is responsible for stable interactions with CK2α [20,30,32a] . As a result, it was somewhat unexpected that mutating cysteines 109 and 114 of the zinc finger would have an effect on α-β interactions. Furthermore, Meggio et al. [CITATION_1] demonstrated that recombinant β treated with sulphydryl-modifying reagents fails to form homodimers, but forms α-β dimers and α # β\\αβ # trimers in itro. However, sulphydryl-modifying reagents would exert global effects on the cysteine residues in CK2β and CK2α, so it is not clear that these results were exclusively due to disruption of the zinc finger. Furthermore, the study by Meggio et al. [CITATION_2] failed to access the possible role of post-translational modification of CK2 in i o. Our results conclusively show that the zinc-finger mutant is not able to form tetrameric CK2 complexes both in itro and in i o. One possible model that fits our results is that β-β dimerization induces a conformational change that facilitates interactions with the catalytic CK2 subunits. Alternatively, stable binding of the catalytic subunits may require interactions with both members of a CK2β dimer in a manner such that a monomeric form of CK2β is unable to bind catalytic CK2 subunits. Based on the fact that a dimerization-deficient CK2β mutant is not able to interact with CK2α, this model seems to be plausible.",
  "correct_citation": {
    "[CITATION_1]": "29050659",
    "[CITATION_2]": "29050659"
  },
  "bib_entries": {
    "29050659": {
      "title": "pCMB treatment reveals the essential role of cysteinyl residues in conferring functional competence to the regulatory subunit of protein kinase CK2",
      "abstract": "Abstract To assess the functional role of the four conserved cysteinyl residues in the regulatory β-subunit of protein kinase CK2, the effect of pCMB and other reagents of sulfhydryl groups has been investigated. The pCMB-treated β-subunit has lost its ability to form either homodimers or regular α 2 β 2 heterotetramers with the catalytic subunit. It also fails to increase catalytic activity toward peptide substrates and to mediate the stimulatory effect of polylysine. The pCMB-treated β-subunit, however, is still able to prevent calmodulin phosphorylation and to physically interact with the α-subunit to form inactive complexes whose sedimentation coefficient is lower than that of CK2 holoenzyme. These inactive complexes upon treatment with reducing agents like DTT are converted into a fully active heterotetrameric holoenzyme."
    }
  }
